This is the first time I've commented on any of your videos, although I've been a participant in the YWA community for two years now. This past June, I got a concussion that forced me to take a leave of absence from graduate school. In addition to feeling pretty cruddy as I recovered, I also became severely anxious and depressed (I started doing yoga to treat my anxiety), especially because I feel my future with my education/career has become more uncertain with this injury.

When I felt more physically able, I started doing yoga again with this 30-day challenge. It has been disheartening to start again with almost no physical strength. I haven't been able to do this journey every day in a row, but here I am, three months after suffering in bed for days when I tried to watch a screen, proud to have done yoga for 16 days.

The thing that I love about myself today is my courage. I was intimidated by the length of this video and was worried I would not be able to complete it. I wasn't able to get into every position (half-moon, anyone?) but I did finish, and I didn't beat myself up for not doing it "perfectly". Just like how I don't have to hit every complicated pose to have a good practice, I have begun to internalize that I have worth beyond just completing my degree and holding a high-profile career. It has taken courage to change my whole mindset about what having a good life means. Even if my injury does keep me from finishing grad school, I will be able to accept what comes. 

Thank you, Adriene. Namaste to all <3
There certainly is no other way to live. No turning back now (:

 but I felt like something has been missing.

It's as simple as that but sometimes I'm too caught up to realise.
However, sooner or later I do in fact realis it might just take me a little longer.

A lot of times we do know what we need and what we have to do to find what feels good but it happens that we force things and want to have everything as soon as possible.

Eventually, when we really take time to slow down it really changes the game.

That's what I've learned from you.

Adriene, THANK YOU. Practices like this are things that remind me that I am me, regardless of others' perceptions. It's during these self love meditations that I look inside and find confidence to continue in my life as a trans person. I am non-binary and trans-feminine and I've dealt with so much body dysphoria and identity crises which have led to me almost taking my life. When I do practices like this, I realize that I am worthy. That I am valid. I realize that I owe myself happiness and that I shouldn't feel guilty about who I am and who I want to be, because that simply is not going to go away. I have found so much self acceptance through your videos and yoga. What you are doing is revolutionary. The world NEEDS this so much. Self acceptance is the first step towards accepting everyone around us. Namaste <3

Thank you for this practice. I've gained a bit of weight over the past few months, a lot of it due to severe anxiety, depression, and stress that's kept me from being able to work for the past three months. Today, I needed to go shopping for a few clothing items to replace ones I've worn through, and I couldn't even work up the courage to try anything on because I couldn't stand the thought of looking at myself in the mirror. My boyfriend was outside waiting for me, and when we got back to the car, he asked me to make a commitment right there to start loving myself as much as I possibly could. At 7 pm, finally I worked up the resolve to come to YWA for day 16. When I saw it was about self love, I was excited and scared. I was one of the people who started to cry when I couldn't think of a reason to love myself. I sat down in frustration when I fell out of a standing split. Then I picked myself back up and thought of how you always tell us to accept where we're at today. Some days can be so mentally draining but I think the journey is worth it, and thank you so much for being such a massive part of my life every day. Namaste :) <3

I'm 61 years old and have never worked a yoga practice. 

I'm a musician by night and a freelance stylist by day, hauling heavy bags of merchandise, bending over sets, crawling over or under photographic equipment, often moving walls and heavy surfaces‚Äîrarely off my feet. 

While I'm grateful for not sitting at a desk all day, my work has taken a toll on my body as I've aged and for the last four or five years, I've taken ibuprofen almost daily. A friend recommended your 30 Day Yoga practice and I then moved straight into True 30 Day. It has made me aware of my breath, of my posture (standing and sitting), aware that I need to stretch off and on during the day. 

I had a very physical work day on Thursday and really noticed how different I felt: stronger, sturdier, more flexible, less tired at days end. I am convinced, after 46 straight days of yoga, that I not only need but actually WANT to do this every day‚Äîfor the remainder of my days. It has pretty much been a life changer for me and I can't remember the last time I popped an ibuprofen. 

(Bonus: I stumbled on the fact that you and Hilah are pals from Austin‚Äîha!) 

Thank you for the (not annoying!) way you are offering yoga to the masses‚Äîsupportive and inclusive of all bodies, ages and abilities. 

Namaste.

Adriene, you have changed my life.

When I started doing yoga a year and a half ago, I was a depressed, slightly overweight person looking for a different way of life.  A way of life in which I loved myself. Back then I wanted to be someone completely different, but now I have fallen in love. With yoga, me and life. I started yoga to get fit, and while I have gotten fit, I have also become a more free and happy person. I have begun to conquer my fears, living a dream that I never thought I could live and have learnt to be at peace with myself. The last time I did a self love practice, I couldn't find a single thing I loved. I hated my size and my body. But now i've realised, I'm not a size. I'm not a number. I am this awesome, loving, funny person who is super lovely to be around. Today, the list of things I loved about myself included everything- the faults, the mistakes and the good parts. It's definitely been a journey falling in love with myself, and I'm glad it didn't take me longer than my sixteen years. so  I can live the rest of my life happy in my own skin and having my own back.  Sorry for the long comment, but I do aspire to become a writer someday. üòâ Thank you for this journey and everything, and I'm sending you all the love my heart can hold.
To anybody else going through a similar journey too, I'm sending you lots of love and light.‚ù§‚ù§
